# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wine-compatibility-layer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] In software engineering, a **compatibility layer** is an interface that allows binaries for a legacy or foreign system to run on a host system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] This translates system calls for the foreign system into native system calls for the host system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] With some libraries for the foreign system, this will often be sufficient to run foreign binaries on the host system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] A hardware compatibility layer consists of tools that allow hardware emulation.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] A compatibility layer avoids both the complexity and the speed penalty of full hardware emulation.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] Some programs may even run faster than the original, *e.g.* some Linux applications running on FreeBSD's Linux compatibility layer may perform better than the same applications on Red Hat Linux.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] Benchmarks are occasionally run on Wine to compare it to Windows NT-based operating systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] Even on similar systems, the details of implementing a compatibility layer can be quite intricate and troublesome; a good example is the IRIX binary compatibility layer in the MIPS architecture version of NetBSD.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] A compatibility layer requires the host system's CPU to be (upwardly) compatible to that of the foreign system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] For example, a Microsoft Windows compatibility layer is not possible on PowerPC hardware because Windows requires an x86 CPU.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] Hardware compatibility layers involve tools that allow hardware emulation.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/compatibility-layer] Some hardware compatibility layers involve breakout boxes because breakout boxes can provide compatibility for certain computer buses that are otherwise incompatible with the machine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D contains many commands for 3D computer graphics rendering; however, since version 8, Direct3D has superseded the DirectDraw framework and also taken responsibility for the rendering of 2D graphics.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Microsoft strives to continually update Direct3D to support the latest technology available on 3D graphics cards.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D offers full vertex software emulation but no pixel software emulation for features not available in hardware.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The API does include a *Reference Rasterizer* (or REF device), which emulates a generic graphics card in software, although it is too slow for most real-time 3D applications and is typically only used for debugging.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] A new real-time software rasterizer, *WARP*, designed to emulate the complete feature set of Direct3D 10.1, is included with Windows 7 and Windows Vista Service Pack 2 with the Platform Update; its performance is said to be on par with lower-end 3D cards on multi-core CPUs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] As part of DirectX, Direct3D is available for Windows 95 and above, and is the base for the vector graphics API on the different versions of Xbox console systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Wine compatibility layer, a free software reimplementation of several Windows APIs, includes an implementation of Direct3D.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D's main competitor is Khronos' OpenGL and its follow-on Vulkan.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Fahrenheit was an attempt by Microsoft and SGI to unify OpenGL and Direct3D in the 1990s, but was eventually cancelled.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] In 1992, Servan Keondjian, Doug Rabson and Kate Seekings started a company named RenderMorphics, which developed a 3D graphics API named Reality Lab, which was used in medical imaging and CAD software.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Microsoft bought RenderMorphics in February 1995, bringing its staff on board to implement a 3D graphics engine for Windows 95.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D initially implemented an "immediate mode" 3D API and layered upon it a "retained mode" 3D API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Both types of API were already offered with the second release of Reality Lab before Direct3D was released.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Like other DirectX APIs, such as DirectDraw, both were based on COM.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The retained mode API was a scene graph API that attained little adoption.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Game developers clamored for more direct control of the hardware's activities than the Direct3D retained mode could provide.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Only two games that sold a significant volume, *Lego Island* and *Lego Rock Raiders*, were based on the Direct3D retained mode, so Microsoft did not update the retained mode API after DirectX 3.0.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] For DirectX 2.0 and 3.0, the Direct3D immediate mode used an "execute buffer" programming model that Microsoft hoped hardware vendors would support directly.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Execute buffers were intended to be allocated in hardware memory and parsed by the hardware to perform the 3D rendering.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] They were considered extremely awkward to program at the time, however, hindering adoption of the new API and prompting calls for Microsoft to adopt OpenGL as the official 3D rendering API for games as well as workstation applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Rather than adopt OpenGL as a gaming API, Microsoft chose to continue improving Direct3D, not only to be competitive with OpenGL, but to compete more effectively with other proprietary APIs such as 3dfx's Glide.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] From the beginning, the immediate mode also supported Talisman's tiled rendering with the BeginScene/EndScene methods of the IDirect3DDevice interface.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] No substantive changes were planned to Direct3D for **DirectX 4.0**, which was scheduled to ship in late 1996 and then cancelled.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] In December 1996, a team in Redmond took over development of the Direct3D Immediate Mode, while the London-based RenderMorphics team continued work on the Retained Mode.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Redmond team added the DrawPrimitive API that eliminated the need for applications to construct execute buffers, making Direct3D more closely resemble other immediate mode rendering APIs such as Glide and OpenGL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The first beta of DrawPrimitive shipped in February 1997, and the final version shipped with **DirectX 5.0** in August 1997.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Besides introducing an easier-to-use immediate mode API, DirectX 5.0 added the SetRenderTarget method that enabled Direct3D devices to write their graphical output to a variety of DirectDraw surfaces.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] A minor update to **DirectX 6.0** came in the February, 1999 DirectX 6.1 update.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Besides adding DirectMusic support for the first time, this release improved support for Intel Pentium III 3D extensions.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] A confidential memo sent in 1997 shows Microsoft planning to announce full support for Talisman in DirectX 6.0, but the API ended up being cancelled (See the Microsoft Talisman page for details).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D was not considered to be user friendly, but as of DirectX version 8.1, many usability problems were resolved.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 8 contained many powerful 3D graphics features, such as vertex shaders, pixel shaders, fog, bump mapping and texture mapping.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Windows Vista includes a major update to the Direct3D API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Originally called WGF 2.0 (Windows Graphics Foundation 2.0), then DirectX 10 and DirectX Next, **Direct3D 10** features an updated shader model 4.0 and optional interruptibility for shader programs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] In this model shaders still consist of fixed stages as in previous versions, but all stages support a nearly unified interface, as well as a unified access paradigm for resources such as textures and shader constants.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The language itself has been extended to be more expressive, including integer operations, a greatly increased instruction count, and more C-like language constructs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Windows XP and earlier are not supported by DirectX 10.0 and above.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Furthermore, Direct3D 10 dropped support for the retained mode API which had been a part of Direct3D since the beginning, making Windows Vista incompatible with 3D games that had used the retained mode API as their rendering engine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Unlike prior versions of the API, Direct3D 10 no longer uses "capability bits" (or "caps") to indicate which features are supported on a given graphics device.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Instead, it defines a minimum standard of hardware capabilities which must be supported for a display system to be "Direct3D 10 compatible".
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This is a significant departure, with the goal of streamlining application code by removing capability-checking code and special cases based on the presence or absence of specific capabilities.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Because Direct3D 10 hardware was comparatively rare after the initial release of Windows Vista and because of the massive install base of non-Direct3D 10 compatible graphics cards, the first Direct3D 10-compatible games still provide Direct3D 9 render paths.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Examples of such titles are games originally written for Direct3D 9 and ported to Direct3D 10 after their release, such as *Company of Heroes*, or games originally developed for Direct3D 9 with a Direct3D 10 path retrofitted later during their development, such as *Hellgate: London* or *Crysis*.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The DirectX 10 SDK became available in February 2007.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 10.1 sets a few more image quality standards for graphics vendors, and gives developers more control over image quality.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Features include finer control over anti-aliasing (both multisampling and supersampling with per sample shading and application control over sample position) and more flexibilities to some of the existing features (cubemap arrays and independent blending modes).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Unlike Direct3D 10 which strictly required Direct3D 10-class hardware and driver interfaces, Direct3D 10.1 runtime can run on Direct3D 10.0 hardware using a concept of "feature levels", but new features are supported exclusively by new hardware which expose feature level 10_1.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The only available Direct3D 10.1 hardware as of June 2008 were the Radeon HD 3000 series and Radeon HD 4000 series from ATI; in 2009, they were joined by Chrome 430/440GT GPUs from S3 Graphics and select lower-end models in GeForce 200 series from Nvidia.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] In 2011, Intel chipsets started supporting Direct3D 10.1 with the introduction of Intel HD Graphics 2000 (GMA HD).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Direct3D 11 runtime is able to run on Direct3D 9 and 10.x-class hardware and drivers using the concept of "feature levels", expanding on the functionality first introduced in Direct3D 10.1 runtime.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] There are three "10 Level 9" profiles which encapsulate various capabilities of popular DirectX 9.0a cards, and Direct3D 10, 10.1, and 11 each have a separate feature level; each upper level is a strict superset of a lower level.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Tessellation was earlier considered for Direct3D 10, but was later abandoned.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] GPUs such as Radeon R600 feature a tessellation engine that can be used with Direct3D 9/10/10.1 and OpenGL, but it's not compatible with Direct3D 11 (according to Microsoft).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Older graphics hardware such as Radeon 8xxx, GeForce 3/4 had support for another form of tesselation (RT patches, N patches) but those technologies never saw substantial use.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] As such, their support was dropped from newer hardware.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Microsoft has also hinted at other features such as order independent transparency, which was never exposed by the Direct3D API but supported almost transparently by early Direct3D hardware such as Videologic's PowerVR line of chips.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Other notable features are the addition of two new texture compression algorithms for more efficient packing of high quality and HDR/alpha textures and an increased texture cache.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] First seen in the Release Candidate version, Windows 7 integrates the first released Direct3D 11 support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Platform Update for Windows Vista includes full-featured Direct3D 11 runtime and DXGI 1.1 update, as well as other related components from Windows 7 like WARP, Direct2D, DirectWrite, and WIC.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] WARP has been updated to support feature level 11_1.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Platform Update for Windows 7 includes a limited set of features from Direct3D 11.1, though components that depend on WDDM 1.2 – such as feature level 11_1 and its related APIs, or quad buffering for stereoscopic rendering – are not present.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 11.X is a superset of DirectX 11.2 running on the Xbox One.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] It includes some features, such as draw bundles, that were later announced as part of DirectX 12.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Pipeline state objects (PSOs) have evolved from Direct3D 11, and the new concise pipeline states mean that the process has been simplified.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] DirectX 11 offered flexibility in how its states could be altered, to the detriment of performance.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Simplifying the process and unifying the pipelines (e.g. pixel shader states) lead to a more streamlined process, significantly reducing the overheads and allowing the graphics card to draw more calls for each frame.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Root signatures introduce configurations to link command lists to resources required by shaders.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] They define the layout of resources that shaders will use and specify what resources will be bound to the pipeline.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] A graphics command list has both a graphics and compute root signature, while a compute command list will have only a compute root signature.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] These root signatures are completely independent of each other.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] While the root signature lays out the types of data for shaders to use, it does not define or map the actual memory or data.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Root parameters are one type of entry in a root signature.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The actual values of the root parameters that are modified at runtime are called root arguments.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Within Direct3D 11, the commands are sent from the CPU to the GPU one by one, and the GPU works through these commands sequentially.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This means that commands are bottlenecked by the speed at which the CPU can send these commands in a linear fashion.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Within DirectX 12 these commands are sent as command lists, containing all the required information within a single package.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The GPU is then capable of computing and executing this command in one single process, without having to wait on any additional information from the CPU.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Where previously commands were just taken, used, and then forgotten by the GPU, bundles can be reused.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This decreases the workload of the GPU and means repeated assets can be used much faster.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] While resource binding is fairly convenient in Direct3D 11 for developers at the moment, its inefficiency means several modern hardware capabilities are being drastically underused.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] When a game engine needed resources in DX11, it had to draw the data from scratch every time, meaning repeat processes and unnecessary uses.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] In Direct3D 12, descriptor heaps and tables mean the most often used resources can be allocated by developers in tables, which the GPU can quickly and easily access.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This can contribute to better performance than Direct3D 11 on equivalent hardware, but it also entails more work for the developer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Dynamic Heaps are also a feature of Direct3D 12.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 12 features explicit multi-adapter support, allowing the explicit control of multiple GPUs (mGPU) configuration systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Such configurations can be built with graphics adapter of the same hardware vendor as well of different hardware vendor together.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] An experimental support of D3D 12 for Windows 7 SP1 has been released by Microsoft in 2019 via a dedicated NuGet package.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D is a Microsoft DirectX API subsystem component.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The aim of Direct3D is to abstract the communication between a graphics application and the graphics hardware drivers.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] It is presented like a thin abstract layer at a level comparable to GDI (see attached diagram).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D contains numerous features that GDI lacks.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D is an *Immediate mode* graphics API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] It provides a low-level interface to every video card 3D function (*transformations, clipping, lighting*, *materials*, *textures*, *depth buffering* and so on).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] It once had a higher level *Retained mode* component, now officially discontinued.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D immediate mode presents three main abstractions: *devices*, *resources* and *Swap Chains* (see attached diagram).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] *Devices* are responsible for rendering the 3D scene.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] They provide an interface with different rendering capabilities.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] For example, the mono device provides white and black rendering, while the RGB device renders in color.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Every device contains at least one *swap chain*.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] A *swap chain* is made up of one or more back buffer surfaces.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Moreover, devices contain a collection of *resources*; specific data used during rendering.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Microsoft Direct3D 11 API defines a process to convert a group of vertices, textures, buffers, and state into an image on the screen.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This process is described as a rendering pipeline with several distinct stages.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Vertex Shader**: Performs operations on a single vertex at a time, such as transformations, skinning, or lighting.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Hull-Shader**: Performs operations on sets of patch control points, and generates additional data known as patch constants.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Tessellator**: Subdivides geometry to create higher-order representations of the hull.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Domain-Shader**: Performs operations on vertices output by the tessellation stage, in much the same way as a vertex shader.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Geometry Shader**: Processes entire primitives such as triangles, points, or lines.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Given a primitive, this stage discards it, or generates one or more new primitives.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Stream-Output**: Can write out the previous stage's results to memory.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This is useful to recirculate data back into the pipeline.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Rasterizer**: Converts primitives into pixels, feeding these pixels into the pixel shader.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The Rasterizer may also perform other tasks such as clipping what is not visible, or interpolating vertex data into per-pixel data.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Pixel Shader**: Determines the final pixel color to be written to the render target and can also calculate a depth value to be written to the depth buffer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] **Output-Merger**: Merges various types of output data (pixel shader values, alpha blending, depth/stencil...) to build the final result.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The pipeline stages illustrated with a round box are fully programmable.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] The application provides a shader program that describes the exact operations to be completed for that stage.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Many stages are optional and can be disabled altogether.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] In Direct3D 5 to 9, when new versions of the API introduced support for new hardware capabilities, most of them were optional – each graphics vendor maintained their own set of supported features in addition to the basic required functionality.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Support for individual features had to be determined using "capability bits" or "caps", making cross-vendor graphics programming a complex task.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 10 introduced a much simplified set of mandatory hardware requirements based on most popular Direct3D 9 capabilities which all supporting graphics cards had to adhere to, with only a few optional capabilities for supported texture formats and operations.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 10.1 added a few new mandatory hardware requirements, and to remain compatible with 10.0 hardware and drivers, these features were encapsulated in two sets called "feature levels", with 10.1 level forming a superset of 10.0 level.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] As Direct3D 11.0, 11.1 and 12 added support for new hardware, new mandatory capabilities were further grouped in upper feature levels.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 11 also introduced "10level9", a subset of the Direct3D 10 API with three feature levels encapsulating various Direct3D 9 cards with WDDM drivers, and Direct3D 11.1 re-introduced a few optional features for all levels, which were expanded in Direct3D 11.2 and later versions.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] This approach allows developers to unify the rendering pipeline and use a single version of the API on both newer and older hardware, taking advantage of performance and usability improvements in the newer runtime.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Each upper level is a strict superset of a lower level, with only a few new or previously optional features that move to the core functionality on an upper level.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] More advanced features in a major revision of the Direct3D API such as new shader models and rendering stages are only exposed on up-level hardware.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Separate capabilities exist to indicate support for specific texture operations and resource formats; these are specified per each texture format using a combination of capability flags.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Feature levels use underscore as a delimiter (i.e.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] "12_1"), while API/runtime versions use dot (i.e.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 12 for Windows 10 requires graphics hardware conforming to feature levels 11_0 and 11_1 which support virtual memory address translations and requires WDDM 2.0 drivers.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] There are two new feature levels, 12_0 and 12_1, which include some new features exposed by Direct3D 12 that are optional on levels 11_0 and 11_1.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Some previously optional features are realigned as baseline on levels 11_0 and 11_1.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Shader Model 6.0 has been released with Windows 10 Creators Update and requires Windows 10 Anniversary Update, WDDM 2.1 drivers.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Direct3D 12 introduces a revamped resource binding model which allows explicit control of memory.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Abstract "resource view" objects are now represented with resource descriptors, which are allocated using memory heaps and tables.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Resource Binding tiers define maximum number of resources that can be addressed using CBV (constant buffer view), SRV (shader resource view) and UAV (unordered access view), as well as texture sampler units.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p01] Tier 3 hardware allows fully bindless resources only restricted by the size of the descriptor heap, while Tier 1 and Tier 2 hardware impose some limits on the number of descriptors ("views") that can be used simultaneously.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] WDDM driver model in Windows Vista and higher supports arbitrarily large number of execution contexts (or threads) in hardware or in software.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Windows XP only supported multitasked access to Direct3D, where separate applications could execute in different windows and be hardware accelerated, and the OS had limited control about what the GPU could do and the driver could switch execution threads arbitrarily.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] The ability to execute the runtime in a multi-threaded mode has been introduced with Direct3D 11 runtime.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Each execution context is presented with a resource view of the GPU.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Execution contexts are protected from each other, however a rogue or badly written app can take control of the execution in the user-mode driver and could potentially access data from another process within GPU memory by sending modified commands.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Though protected from access by another app, a well-written app still needs to protect itself against failures and device loss caused by other applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] The OS manages the threads all by itself, allowing the hardware to switch from one thread to the other when appropriate, and also handles memory management and paging (to system memory and to disk) via integrated OS-kernel memory management.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Finer-grained context switching, i.e. being able to switch two execution threads at the shader-instruction level instead of the single-command level or even batch of commands, was introduced in WDDM/DXGI 1.2 which shipped with Windows 8.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] This overcomes a potential scheduling problem when application would have very long execution of a single command/batch of commands and will have to be terminated by the OS watchdog timer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] WDDM 2.0 and DirectX 12 have been reengineered to allow fully multithreaded draw calls.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] This was achieved by making all resources immutable (i.e. read-only), serializing the rendering states and using draw call bundles.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] This avoids complex resource management in the kernel-mode driver, making possible multiple reentrant calls to the user-mode driver via concurrent executions contexts supplied by separate rendering threads in the same application.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Direct3D Mobile is derived from Direct3D but has a smaller memory footprint.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Windows CE provides Direct3D Mobile support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] The following alternative implementations of Direct3D API exist.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] There are several functions that provide complex operations over 3D meshes like tangent-space computation, mesh simplification, precomputed radiance transfer, optimizing for vertex cache friendliness and stripification, and generators for 3D text meshes.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] 2D features include classes for drawing screen-space lines, text and sprite based particle systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] Spatial functions include various intersection routines, conversion from/to barycentric coordinates and bounding box/sphere generators.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] D3DX is provided as a dynamic link library (DLL).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] D3DX is deprecated from Windows 8 onward and can't be used in Windows Store apps.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] DXUT (also called the sample framework) is a layer built on top of the Direct3D API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] The framework is designed to help the programmer spend less time with mundane tasks, such as creating a window, creating a device, processing Windows messages and handling device events.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/direct3d-p02] DXUT have been removed with the Windows SDK 8.0 and now distributed as source via CodePlex.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] DXVK was first developed by Philip "doitsujin" Rebohle to support Direct3D 11 games only driven by frustration over poor compatibility and low performance of Wine's Direct3D 11 to OpenGL translation layer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] In 2018, the developer was sponsored by Valve to work on the project full-time in order to advance compatibility of the Linux version of Steam with Windows games.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] In 2019, DXVK received Direct3D 9 support by merging with d9vk.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] In November 2022, version 2.0 was released, introducing improvements to Direct3D 9 memory management, shader compilation, state cache, and support for Direct3D 11 feature level 12_1.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] Released on January 24, 2023, version 2.1 implemented HDR support and improved quality for certain old games.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] Released on May 12, 2023, version 2.2 added D3D11On12 support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] Released on July 10, 2024, version 2.4 added support for Direct3D 8.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] Released on November 11, 2024, version 2.5 features an overhauled memory and resource management which resulted in VRAM savings up to 1 GB in certain games.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] Direct3D 8 and 9 received support for software cursor.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] In June 2026, DXVK 3.0 replaced its legacy DXBC shader translation code with `dxbc-spirv`, reducing memory use in some games and moving more shader compilation work off the application thread.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] The release also began requiring Vulkan 1.4-era driver support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] Users of AMD RDNA 1.0 and RDNA 2.0 architectures on Windows are advised against using DXVK 3.0 because "Windows driver for these GPUs no longer receives feature updates, can only use the slow legacy binding model, and suffers from severe performance issues that are not seen on any other driver".
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] D7VK is a DXVK fork that uses its D3D9 back-end to implement support for Direct3D 3, 5, 6 and 7.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] The project does not expect to be upstreamed or merged with the parent.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dxvk] The use of Wine/DXVK has gotten users banned from some online gaming platforms because these layers have been classified as illegitimate by their anti-cheat systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Data files with the same file format as a DLL, but with different file extensions and possibly containing only resource sections, can be called *resource DLLs*.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Examples of such DLLs include *icon libraries*, sometimes having the extension `ICL`, and font files, having the extensions `FON` and `FOT`.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The first versions of Microsoft Windows ran programs together in a single address space.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Every program was meant to co-operate by yielding the CPU to other programs so that the graphical user interface (GUI) could multitask and be maximally responsive.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] All operating-system level operations were provided by the underlying operating system: MS-DOS.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] All higher-level services were provided by Windows Libraries "Dynamic Link Library".
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The Drawing API, Graphics Device Interface (GDI), was implemented in a DLL called `GDI.EXE`, the user interface in `USER.EXE`.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] These extra layers on top of DOS had to be shared across all running Windows programs, not just to enable Windows to work in a machine with less than a megabyte of RAM, but to enable the programs to co-operate with each other.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The code in GDI needed to translate drawing commands to operations on specific devices.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] On the display, it had to manipulate pixels in the frame buffer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] When drawing to a printer, the API calls had to be transformed into requests to a printer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Although it could have been possible to provide hard-coded support for a limited set of devices (like the Color Graphics Adapter display, the HP LaserJet Printer Command Language), Microsoft chose a different approach.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] GDI would work by loading different pieces of code, called "device drivers", to work with different output devices.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The same architectural concept that allowed GDI to load different device drivers also allowed the Windows shell to load different Windows programs, and for these programs to invoke API calls from the shared USER and GDI libraries.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In a conventional non-shared static library, sections of code are simply added to the calling program when its executable is built at the "linking" phase; if two programs call the same routine, the routine is included in both the programs during the linking stage of the two.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] With dynamic linking, shared code is placed into a single, separate file.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The programs that call this file are connected to it at run time, with the operating system (or, in the case of early versions of Windows, the OS-extension), performing the binding.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] For those early versions of Windows (1.0 to 3.11), the DLLs were the foundation for the entire GUI.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This notion of building up the operating system from a collection of dynamically loaded libraries is a core concept of Windows that persists as of 2015.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] DLLs provide the standard benefits of shared libraries, such as modularity.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Modularity allows changes to be made to code and data in a single self-contained DLL shared by several applications without any change to the applications themselves.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Another benefit of modularity is the use of generic interfaces for plug-ins.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] A single interface may be developed which allows old as well as new modules to be integrated seamlessly at run-time into pre-existing applications, without any modification to the application itself.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This concept of dynamic extensibility is taken to the extreme with the Component Object Model, the underpinnings of ActiveX.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In Windows 1.x, 2.x and 3.x, all Windows applications shared the same address space as well as the same memory.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] A DLL was only loaded once into this address space; from then on, all programs using the library accessed it.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The library's data was shared across all the programs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This could be used as an indirect form of inter-process communication, or it could accidentally corrupt the different programs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] With the introduction of 32-bit libraries in Windows 95, every process ran in its own address space.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] While the DLL code may be shared, the data is private except where shared data is explicitly requested by the library.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] That said, large swathes of Windows 95, Windows 98 and Windows Me were built from 16-bit libraries, which limited the performance of the Pentium Pro microprocessor when launched, and ultimately limited the stability and scalability of the DOS-based versions of Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Although DLLs are the core of the Windows architecture, they have several drawbacks, collectively called "DLL hell".
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] As of 2015 Microsoft promotes .NET Framework as one solution to the problems of DLL hell, although they now promote virtualization-based solutions such as Microsoft Virtual PC and Microsoft Application Virtualization, because they offer superior isolation between applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] An alternative mitigating solution to DLL hell has been to implement side-by-side assembly.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Since DLLs are essentially the same as EXEs, the choice of which to produce as part of the linking process is for clarity, since it is possible to export functions and data from either.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] DLLs provide a mechanism for shared code and data, allowing a developer of shared code/data to upgrade functionality without requiring applications to be re-linked or re-compiled.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] From the application development point of view, Windows and OS/2 can be thought of as a collection of DLLs that are upgraded, allowing applications for one version of the OS to work in a later one, provided that the OS vendor has ensured that the interfaces and functionality are compatible.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] DLLs execute in the memory space of the calling process and with the same access permissions, which means there is little overhead in their use, but also that there is no protection for the calling program if the DLL has any sort of bug.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In Windows API, DLL files are organized into *sections*.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Each section has its own set of attributes, such as being writable or read-only, executable (for code) or non-executable (for data), and so on.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The code in a DLL is usually shared among all the processes that use the DLL; that is, they occupy a single place in physical memory, and do not take up space in the page file.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Windows does not use position-independent code for its DLLs; instead, the code undergoes relocation as it is loaded, fixing addresses for all its entry points at locations which are free in the memory space of the first process to load the DLL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In older versions of Windows, in which all running processes occupied a single common address space, a single copy of the DLL's code would always be sufficient for all the processes.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] However, in newer versions of Windows which use separate address spaces for each program, it is only possible to use the same relocated copy of the DLL in multiple programs if each program has the same virtual addresses free to accommodate the DLL's code.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] If some programs (or their combination of already-loaded DLLs) do not have those addresses free, then an additional physical copy of the DLL's code will need to be created, using a different set of relocated entry points.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] If the physical memory occupied by a code section is to be reclaimed, its contents are discarded, and later reloaded directly from the DLL file as necessary.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In contrast to code sections, the data sections of a DLL are usually private; that is, each process using the DLL has its own copy of all the DLL's data.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Optionally, data sections can be made shared, allowing inter-process communication via this shared memory area.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] However, because user restrictions do not apply to the use of shared DLL memory, this creates a security hole; namely, one process can corrupt the shared data, which will likely cause all other sharing processes to behave undesirably.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] For example, a process running under a guest account can in this way corrupt another process running under a privileged account.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This is an important reason to avoid the use of shared sections in DLLs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] If a DLL is compressed by certain executable packers (e.g.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] UPX), all of its code sections are marked as read and write, and will be unshared.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Read-and-write code sections, much like private data sections, are private to each process.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Thus DLLs with shared data sections should not be compressed if they are intended to be used simultaneously by multiple programs, since each program instance would have to carry its own copy of the DLL, resulting in increased memory consumption.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Like static libraries, import libraries for DLLs are noted by the `.lib` file extension.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] For example, kernel32.dll, the primary dynamic library for Windows's base functions such as file creation and memory management, is linked via `kernel32.lib`.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The usual way to tell an import library from a proper static library is by size: the import library is much smaller as it only contains symbols referring to the actual DLL, to be processed at link-time.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Both nevertheless are Unix ar format files.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Linking to dynamic libraries is usually handled by linking to an import library when building or linking to create an executable file.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The created executable then contains an import address table (IAT) by which all DLL function calls are referenced (each referenced DLL function contains its own entry in the IAT).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] At run-time, the IAT is filled with appropriate addresses that point directly to a function in the separately loaded DLL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In Cygwin/MSYS and MinGW, import libraries are conventionally given the suffix `.dll.a`, combining both the Windows DLL suffix and the Unix ar suffix.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The file format is similar, but the symbols used to mark the imports are different (`_head_foo_dll` vs `__IMPORT_DESCRIPTOR_foo`).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Although its GNU Binutils toolchain can generate import libraries and link to them, it is faster to link to the DLL directly.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] An experimental tool in MinGW called genlib can be used to generate import libs with MSVC-style symbols.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Each function exported by a DLL is identified by a numeric ordinal and optionally a name.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Likewise, functions can be imported from a DLL either by ordinal or by name.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The ordinal represents the position of the function's address pointer in the DLL Export Address table.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] It is common for internal functions to be exported by ordinal only.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] For most Windows API functions only the names are preserved across different Windows releases; the ordinals are subject to change.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Thus, one cannot reliably import Windows API functions by their ordinals.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Importing functions by ordinal provides only slightly better performance than importing them by name: export tables of DLLs are ordered by name, so a binary search can be used to find a function.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The index of the found name is then used to look up the ordinal in the Export Ordinal table.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In 16-bit Windows, the name table was not sorted, so the name lookup overhead was much more noticeable.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] It is also possible to *bind* an executable to a specific version of a DLL, that is, to resolve the addresses of imported functions at compile-time.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] For bound imports, the linker saves the timestamp and checksum of the DLL to which the import is bound.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] At run-time, Windows checks to see if the same version of library is being used, and if so, Windows bypasses processing the imports.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Otherwise, if the library is different from the one which was bound to, Windows processes the imports in a normal way.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Bound executables load somewhat faster if they are run in the same environment that they were compiled for, and exactly the same time if they are run in a different environment, so there is no drawback for binding the imports.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] For example, all the standard Windows applications are bound to the system DLLs of their respective Windows release.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] A good opportunity to bind an application's imports to its target environment is during the application's installation.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This keeps the libraries "bound" until the next OS update.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] It does, however, change the checksum of the executable, so it is not something that can be done with signed programs, or programs that are managed by a configuration management tool that uses checksums (such as MD5 checksums) to manage file versions.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] As more recent Windows versions have moved away from having fixed addresses for every loaded library (for security reasons), the opportunity and value of binding an executable is decreasing.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] DLL files may be explicitly loaded at run-time, a process referred to simply as *run-time dynamic linking* by Microsoft, by using the `LoadLibrary` (or `LoadLibraryEx`) API function.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The `GetProcAddress` API function is used to look up exported symbols by name, and `FreeLibrary` – to unload the DLL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] These functions are analogous to `dlopen`, `dlsym`, and `dlclose` in the POSIX standard API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The procedure for explicit run-time linking is the same in any language that supports pointers to functions, since it depends on the Windows API rather than language constructs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Normally, an application that is linked against a DLL’s import library will fail to start if the DLL cannot be found, because Windows will not run the application unless it can find all of the DLLs that the application may need.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] However an application may be linked against an import library to allow delayed loading of the dynamic library.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In this case, the operating system will not try to find or load the DLL when the application starts; instead, a stub is included in the application by the linker which will try to find and load the DLL through `LoadLibrary` and `GetProcAddress` when one of its functions is called.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] If the DLL cannot be found or loaded, or the called function does not exist, the application will generate an exception, which may be caught and handled appropriately.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] If the application does not handle the exception, it will be caught by the operating system, which will terminate the program with an error message.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The delayed loading mechanism also provides notification hooks, allowing the application to perform additional processing or error handling when the DLL is loaded and/or any DLL function is called.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In a source file, the keyword `library` is used instead of `program`.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] At the end of the file, the functions to be exported are listed in `exports` clause.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Delphi does not need `LIB` files to import functions from DLLs; to link to a DLL, the `external` keyword is used in the function declaration to signal the DLL name, followed by `name` to name the symbol (if different) or `index` to identify the index.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In Visual Basic (VB), only run-time linking is supported; but in addition to using `LoadLibrary` and `GetProcAddress` API functions, *declarations* of imported functions are allowed.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] When importing DLL functions through declarations, VB will generate a run-time error if the `DLL` file cannot be found.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The developer can catch the error and handle it appropriately.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] When creating DLLs in VB, the IDE will only allow creation of ActiveX DLLs, however methods have been created to allow the user to explicitly tell the linker to include a .DEF file which defines the ordinal position and name of each exported function.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This allows the user to create a standard Windows DLL using Visual Basic (Version 6 or lower) which can be referenced through a "Declare" statement.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Microsoft Visual C++ (MSVC) provides several extensions to standard C++ which allow functions to be specified as imported or exported directly in the C++ code; these have been adopted by other Windows C and C++ compilers, including Windows versions of GCC.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] These extensions use the attribute `__declspec` before a function declaration.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Note that when C functions are accessed from C++, they must also be declared as `extern "C"` in C++ code, to inform the compiler that the C linkage should be used.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Besides specifying imported or exported functions using `__declspec` attributes, they may be listed in IMPORT or EXPORTS section of the `DEF` file used by the project.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The `DEF` file is processed by the linker, rather than the compiler, and thus it is not specific to C++.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] DLL compilation will produce both `DLL` and `LIB` files.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The `LIB` file (import library) is used to link against a DLL at compile-time; it is not necessary for run-time linking.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Unless the DLL is a Component Object Model (COM) server, the `DLL` file must be placed in one of the directories listed in the PATH environment variable, in the default system directory, or in the same directory as the program using it.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] COM server DLLs are registered using regsvr32.exe, which places the DLL's location and its globally unique ID (GUID) in the registry.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Programs can then use the DLL by looking up its GUID in the registry to find its location or create an instance of the COM object indirectly using its class identifier and interface identifier.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The following examples show how to use language-specific bindings to import symbols for linking against a DLL at compile-time.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] 'Example.lib' file must be included (assuming that Example.dll is generated) in the project before static linking.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The file 'Example.lib' is automatically generated by the compiler when compiling the DLL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Not executing the above statement would cause linking error as the linker would not know where to find the definition of `AddNumbers`.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The following examples show how to use the run-time loading and linking facilities using language-specific Windows API bindings.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Note that all of the four samples are vulnerable to DLL preloading attacks, since example.dll can be resolved to a place unintended by the author (the current working directory goes *before* system library locations), and thus to a malicious version of the library.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] See the reference for Microsoft's guidance on safe library loading: one should use `SetDllDirectoryW` in `kernel32` to remove the current-directory lookup before any libraries are loaded.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The Python ctypes binding will use POSIX API on POSIX systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The Component Object Model (COM) defines a binary standard to host the implementation of objects in DLL and EXE files.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] It provides mechanisms to locate and version those files as well as a language-independent and machine-readable description of the interface.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Hosting COM objects in a DLL is more lightweight and allows them to share resources with the client process.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] This allows COM objects to implement powerful back-ends to simple GUI front ends such as Visual Basic and ASP.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] They can also be programmed from scripting languages.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Due to a vulnerability commonly known as DLL hijacking, DLL spoofing, DLL preloading or binary planting, many programs will load and execute a malicious DLL contained in the same folder as a data file opened by these programs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] The vulnerability was discovered by Georgi Guninski in 2000.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] In August 2010 it gained worldwide publicity after ACROS Security rediscovered it again and many hundreds of programs were found vulnerable.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/dynamic-link-library] Programs that are run from unsafe locations, i.e. user-writable folders like the *Downloads* or the *Temp* directory, are almost always susceptible to this vulnerability.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The **Windows API**, informally **WinAPI**, is the foundational application programming interface (API) that allows a computer program to access the features of the Microsoft Windows operating system in which the program is running.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Programs typically access this API using system libraries, which are shared libraries.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Each major version of the Windows API has a distinct name that identifies a compatibility aspect of that version.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] For example, Win32 is the major version of Windows API that runs on 32-bit systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The name, Windows API, collectively refers to all versions of this capability of Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Microsoft provides developer support via a software development kit, Microsoft Windows SDK, which includes documentation and tools for building software based on the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] This section lists notable services provided by the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Base services include features such as the file system, devices, processes, threads, and error handling.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] These functions reside in kernel.exe, krnl286.exe or krnl386.exe files on 16-bit Windows, and kernel32.dll and KernelBase.dll on 32 and 64 bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] These files reside in the folder \Windows\System32 on all versions of Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Advanced services include features beyond the kernel like the Windows registry, shutdown/restart the system (or abort), start/stop/create a Windows service, manage user accounts.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] These functions reside in advapi32.dll and advapires32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Graphics Device Interface (GDI) component provides features to output graphics content to monitors, printers, and other output devices.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] It resides in gdi.exe on 16-bit Windows, and gdi32.dll on 32-bit Windows in user-mode.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Kernel-mode GDI support is provided by `win32k.sys` which communicates directly with the graphics driver.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The User Interface component provides features to create and manage screen windows and most basic controls, such as buttons and scrollbars, receive mouse and keyboard input, and other functions associated with the graphical user interface (GUI) part of Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] This functional unit resides in user.exe on 16-bit Windows, and user32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Since Windows XP versions, the basic controls reside in comctl32.dll, together with the common controls (Common Control Library).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Common Dialog Box Library provides standard dialog boxes to open and save files, choose color and font, etc.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The library resides in a file called commdlg.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comdlg32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] It is grouped under the *User Interface* category of the API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Common Control Library provides access to advanced user interface controls, including things like status bars, progress bars, toolbars and tabs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The library resides in a DLL file called commctrl.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comctl32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Windows Shell component provides access to the operating system shell.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The component resides in shell.dll on 16-bit Windows, and shell32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Shell Lightweight Utility Functions are in shlwapi.dll.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Network Services provide access to the various networking abilities of the operating system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Its subcomponents include NetBIOS, Winsock, NetDDE, remote procedure call (RPC) and many more.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] This component resides in netapi32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Internet Explorer (IE) web browser exposes APIs and as such could be considered part of the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] IE has been included with the operating system since Windows 95 OSR2 and has provided web-related services to applications since Windows 98.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Windows API is a C language-based API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Functions and data structures are consumable via C syntax by including windows.h, but the API can be consumed via any programming language that can inter-operate with the API data structures and calling conventions for function calls and callbacks.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Of note, the implementation of API functions has been developed in several languages other than C.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Despite the fact that C is not an object-oriented programming (OOP) language, the Windows API is somewhat object-oriented due to its use of handles.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Various other technologies from Microsoft and others make this object-oriented aspect more apparent by using an OOP language such as C++ — see Microsoft Foundation Class Library (MFC), Visual Component Library (VCL), GDI+.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Of note, Windows 8 provides the Windows API and the WinRT API, which is implemented in C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Windows.pas is a Delphi unit that exposes the features of Windows API – the Pascal equivalent of windows.h.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Many Microsoft technologies use the Windows API—as most software running on Windows does.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] As middle-ware between Windows API and an application, the following technologies provide some access to Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Some technologies are described as wrapping Windows API, but this is debatable since they don't provide or expose all of the capabilities of Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Although almost all Windows programs use the Windows API, on the Windows NT line of operating systems, programs that start early in the Windows startup process use the Native API instead.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Windows API has always exposed a large part of the underlying structure of the Windows systems to programmers.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] This had the advantage of giving them much flexibility and power over their applications, but also creates great responsibility in how applications handle various low-level, sometimes tedious, operations that are associated with a graphical user interface.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] For example, a beginning C programmer will often write the simple "hello world" as their first assignment.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The working part of the program is only a single printf line within the main subroutine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Charles Petzold, who wrote several books about programming for the Windows API, said: "The original hello world program in the Windows 1.0 SDK was a bit of a scandal.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] HELLO.C was about 150 lines long, and the HELLO.RC resource script had another 20 or so more lines.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] (...) Veteran programmers often curled up in horror or laughter when encountering the Windows hello-world program." Petzold explains that while it was the first Windows sample programs developers were introduced to, it was quite "fancy" and more complex than needed.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Tired of people ridiculing the length of the sample, he eventually reduced it to a simple MessageBox call.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Over the years, various changes and additions were made to Windows systems, and the Windows API changed and grew to reflect this.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Windows API for Windows 1.0 supported fewer than 450 function calls, whereas modern versions of the Windows API support thousands.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] However, in general, the interface remained fairly consistent, and an old Windows 1.0 application will still look familiar to a programmer who is used to the modern Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Microsoft has made an effort to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] To achieve this, when developing new versions of Windows, Microsoft sometimes implemented workarounds to allow compatibility with third-party software that used the prior version in an undocumented or even inadvisable way.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Raymond Chen, a Microsoft developer who works on the Windows API, has said: "I could probably write for months solely about bad things apps do and what we had to do to get them to work again (often in spite of themselves).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Which is why I get particularly furious when people accuse Microsoft of maliciously breaking applications during OS upgrades.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] One of the largest changes to the Windows API was the transition from Win16 (shipped in Windows 3.1 and older) to Win32 (Windows NT and Windows 95 and up).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] While Win32 was originally introduced with Windows NT 3.1 and Win32s allowed use of a Win32 subset before Windows 95, it was not until Windows 95 that widespread porting of applications to Win32 began.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] To ease the transition, in Windows 95, for developers outside and inside Microsoft, a complex scheme of API thunks was used that could allow 32-bit code to call into 16-bit code (for most of Win16 APIs) and vice versa.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] *Flat thunks* allowed 32-bit code to call into 16-bit libraries, and the scheme was used extensively inside Windows 95's libraries to avoid porting the whole OS to Win32 in one batch.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] In Windows NT, the OS was pure 32-bit, except parts for compatibility with 16-bit applications, and only generic thunks were available to thunk from Win16 to Win32, as for Windows 95.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Platform SDK shipped with a compiler that could produce the code needed for these thunks.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Versions of 64-bit Windows are also able to run 32-bit applications via WoW64.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The SysWOW64 folder located in the Windows folder on the OS drive contains several tools to support 32-bit applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Each version of Microsoft Windows contains a version of Windows API, and almost every new version of Microsoft Windows has introduced additions and changes to the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The name, Windows API, refers to essentially the same capability in each version of Windows, but there is another name for this capability that is based on major architectural aspects of the Windows version that contains it.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] When there was only one version, it was simply called Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Then, when the first major update was made, Microsoft gave it the name Win32 and gave the first version the name Win16.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The term Windows API refers to both versions and all subsequently developed major versions.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Wine project provides a Win32 API compatibility layer for Unix-like platforms, between Linux kernel API and programs written for the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] ReactOS goes a step further and aims to implement the full Windows operating system, working closely with the Wine project to promote code re-use and compatibility.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] DosWin32 and HX DOS Extender are other projects which emulate the Windows API to allow executing simple Windows programs from a DOS command line.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Odin is a project to emulate Win32 on OS/2, superseding the original Win-OS/2 emulation which was based on Microsoft code.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Other minor implementations include the MEWEL and Zinc libraries which were intended to implement a subset of the Win16 API on DOS (see List of platform-independent GUI libraries).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Windows Interface Source Environment (WISE) was a licensing program from Microsoft which allowed developers to recompile and run Windows-based applications on Unix and Macintosh platforms.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] WISE SDKs were based on an emulator of the Windows API that could run on those platforms.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] To develop software that uses the Windows API, a compiler must be able to use the Microsoft-specific DLLs listed above (COM-objects are outside Win32 and assume a certain vtable layout).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The compiler must either handle the header files that expose the interior API function names, or supply such files.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] For the language C++, Zortech (later Symantec, then Digital Mars), Watcom and Borland have all produced well-known commercial compilers that have been used often with Win16, Win32s, and Win32.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Some of them supplied *memory extenders*, allowing Win32 programs to run on Win16 with Microsoft's redistributable Win32s DLL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Zortech compiler was probably one of the first stable and usable C++ compilers for Windows programming, before Microsoft had a C++ compiler.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] For certain classes of applications, the compiler system should also be able to handle interface description language (IDL) files.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Collectively, these prerequisites (compilers, tools, libraries, and headers) are known as the *Microsoft Platform SDK*.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] As of 2016, the MinGW and Cygwin projects also provide such an environment based on the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), using a stand-alone header file set, to make linking against the Win32-specific DLLs simple.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] LCC-Win32 is a C compiler maintained by Jacob Navia, freeware for non-commercial use.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Pelles C is a freeware C compiler maintained by Pelle Orinius.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Free Pascal is a free software Object Pascal compiler that supports the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The MASM32 package is a mature project providing support for the Windows API under Microsoft Macro Assembler (MASM) by using custom made or converted headers and libraries from the Platform SDK.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Flat assembler FASM allows building Windows programs without using an external linker, even when running on Linux.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Windows specific compiler support is also needed for Structured Exception Handling (SEH).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] This system serves two purposes: it provides a substrate on which language-specific exception handling can be implemented, and it is how the kernel notifies applications of exceptional conditions such as dereferencing an invalid pointer or stack overflow.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] The Microsoft/Borland C++ compilers had the ability to use this system as soon as it was introduced in Windows 95 and NT, however the actual implementation was undocumented and had to be reverse engineered for the Wine project and free compilers.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] SEH is based on pushing exception handler frames onto the stack, then adding them to a linked list stored in thread-local storage (the first field of the thread environment block).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] When an exception is thrown, the kernel and base libraries unwind the stack running handlers and filters as they are encountered.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Eventually, every exception unhandled by the application will be dealt with by the default backstop handler, which pops up the Windows common crash dialog.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Microsoft has plans to update the Windows API for modern C++ usage with their `win32metadata` project.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Currently, there is C++/WinRT and "Windows Implementation Library" (WIL) for doing this in modern C++.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/windows-api] Microsoft has also created bindings for other languages, including C# and Rust for calling the Win32 API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine is primarily developed for Linux, macOS and FreeBSD.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Developers can compile Windows applications against WineLib to help port them to Unix-like systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] No code emulation or virtualization occurs, except on Apple silicon Mac computers, where Rosetta 2 is used to translate x86_64 code to ARM code.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] In a 2007 survey by desktoplinux.com of 38,500 Linux desktop users, 31.5% of respondents reported using Wine to run Windows applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] This plurality was larger than all x86 virtualization programs combined and larger than the 27.9% who reported not running Windows applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Bob Amstadt, the initial project leader, and Eric Youngdale started the Wine project in 1993 as a way to run Windows applications on Linux.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It was inspired by two Sun Microsystems products, Wabi for the Solaris operating system, and the Public Windows Interface, which was an attempt to get the Windows API fully reimplemented in the public domain as an ISO standard but rejected due to pressure from Microsoft in 1996.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine originally targeted 16-bit applications for Windows 3.x, but as of 2010 focuses on 32-bit and 64-bit versions which have become the standard on newer operating systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The project originated in discussions on Usenet in comp.os.linux in June 1993.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Alexandre Julliard has led the project since 1994.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The project has proven time-consuming and difficult for the developers, mostly because of incomplete and incorrect documentation of the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] While Microsoft extensively documents most Win32 functions, some areas such as file formats and protocols have no public, complete specification available from Microsoft.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Windows also includes undocumented low-level functions, undocumented behavior and obscure bugs that Wine must duplicate precisely in order to allow some applications to work properly.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Consequently, the Wine team has reverse-engineered many function calls and file formats in such areas as thunking.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The Wine project originally released Wine under the same MIT License as the X Window System, but owing to concern about proprietary versions of Wine not contributing their changes back to the core project, work as of March 2002 has used the LGPL for its licensing.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine officially entered beta with version 0.9 on 25 October 2005.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Version 1.0 was released on 17 June 2008, after 15 years of development.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Development versions are released roughly every two weeks.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine-staging is an independently maintained set of aggressive patches not deemed ready by WineHQ developers for merging into the Wine repository, but still considered useful by the wine-compholio fork.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It mainly covers experimental functions and bug fixes.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Since January 2017, patches in wine-staging have begun to be actively merged into the WineHQ upstream as wine-compholio transferred the project to Alistair Leslie-Hughes, a key WineHQ developer.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of 2019, WineHQ also provides pre-built versions of wine-staging.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The main corporate sponsor of Wine is CodeWeavers, which employs Julliard and many other Wine developers to work on Wine and on CrossOver, CodeWeavers' supported version of Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] CrossOver includes some application-specific tweaks not considered suitable for the upstream version, as well as some additional proprietary components.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Canadian software developer Corel for a time assisted the project, chiefly by employing Julliard and others to work on it.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Corel had an interest in porting WordPerfect Office, its office suite, to Linux (especially Corel Linux).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Corel later cancelled all Linux-related projects after Microsoft made major investments in Corel, stopping their Wine effort.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Other corporate sponsors include Google, which hired CodeWeavers to fix Wine so Picasa ran well enough to be ported directly to Linux using the same binary as on Windows; Google later paid for improvements to Wine's support for Adobe Photoshop CS2.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine is also a regular beneficiary of Google's Summer of Code program.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Valve works with CodeWeavers to develop Proton, a Wine-based compatibility layer for Microsoft Windows games to run on Linux-based operating systems.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Proton includes several patches that upstream Wine does not accept for various reasons, such as Linux-specific implementations of Win32 functions.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The goal of Wine is to implement the Windows APIs fully or partially that are required by programs that the users of Wine wish to run on top of a Unix-like system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The programming interface of Microsoft Windows consists largely of dynamic-link libraries (DLLs).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] These contain a huge number of wrapper sub-routines for the system calls of the kernel, the NTOS kernel-mode program (ntoskrnl.exe).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] A typical Windows program calls some Windows DLLs, which in turn calls user-mode gdi/user32 libraries, which in turn uses the kernel32.dll (win32 subsystem) responsible for dealing with the kernel through system calls.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The system-call layer is considered private to Microsoft programmers as documentation is not publicly available, and published interfaces all rely on subsystems running on top of the kernel.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Besides these, there are a number of programming interfaces implemented as services that run as separate processes.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Applications communicate with user-mode services through RPCs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine implements the Windows application binary interface (ABI) entirely in user space, rather than as a kernel module.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Although wineserver implements some aspects of the Windows kernel, it is not possible to use native Windows drivers with it, due to Wine's underlying architecture.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Configuration of Wine is managed primarily through *control* (wine's implementation of the Windows Control Panel), *regedit* (wine's Windows Registry editor tool), and *winecfg* (a GUI configuration tool), in addition to a multitude of other programmes.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] By default Wine will store configuration files and installed windows applications (unless otherwise specified during install) at *~/.wine*, this directory location is referred to as a Wine Prefix or Bottle.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The *wineprefix* environment variable can be used to specify a different prefix, and using it will thereby change which configuration you are using.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine allows for loading both Windows DLLs and Unix shared objects for its Windows programs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Its built-in implementation of the most basic Windows DLLs, namely NTDLL, KERNEL32, GDI32, and USER32, uses the shared object method because they must use functions in the host operating system as well.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Higher-level libraries, such as WineD3D, are free to use the DLL format.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] In many cases users can choose to load a DLL from Windows instead of the one implemented by Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Doing so can provide functionalities not yet implemented by Wine, but may also cause malfunctions if it relies on something else not present in Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine tracks its state of implementation through automated unit testing done at every git commit.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] While most office software does not make use of complex GPU-accelerated graphics APIs, computer games do.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] To run these games properly, Wine would have to forward the drawing instructions to the host OS, and even translate them to something the host can understand.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] DirectX is a collection of Microsoft APIs for rendering, audio and input.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of 2019, Wine 4.0 contains a DirectX 12 implementation for Vulkan API, and DirectX 11.2 for OpenGL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Direct2D support has been updated to Direct2D 1.2.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine 4.0 also allows Wine to run Vulkan applications by handing draw commands to the host OS, or in the case of macOS, by translating them into the Metal API by MoltenVK.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] through its builtin implementations of these libraries.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Much of Wine's DirectX effort goes into building WineD3D, a translation layer from Direct3D and DirectDraw API calls into OpenGL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of 2019, this component supports up to DirectX 11.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of 12 December 2016, Wine is good enough to run *Overwatch* with D3D11.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Besides being used in Wine, WineD3D DLLs have also been used on Windows itself, allowing for older GPUs to run games using newer DirectX versions and for old DDraw-based games to render correctly.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Some work is ongoing to move the Direct3D backend to Vulkan API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Direct3D 12 support in 4.0 is provided by a "vkd3d" subproject, and WineD3D has in 2019 been experimentally ported to use the Vulkan API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Another implementation, DXVK, translates Direct3D 8, 9, 10, and 11 calls using Vulkan as well and is a separate project.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine, when patched, can alternatively run Direct3D 9 API commands directly via a free and open-source Gallium3D State Tracker (aka Gallium3D GPU driver) without translation into OpenGL API calls.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] In this case, the Gallium3D layer allows a direct pass-through of DX9 drawing commands which results in performance improvements of up to a factor of 2.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of 2020, the project is named Gallium.Nine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It is available now as a separate standalone package and no longer needs a patched Wine version.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine is usually invoked from the command-line interpreter: `wine program.exe`.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] There is the utility `winecfg` that starts a graphical user interface with controls for adjusting basic options.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It is a GUI configuration utility included with Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Winecfg makes configuring Wine easier by making it unnecessary to edit the registry directly, although, if needed, this can be done with the included registry editor (similar to Windows *regedit*).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Some applications require more tweaking than simply installing the application in order to work properly, such as manually configuring Wine to use certain Windows DLLs.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The Wine project does not integrate such workarounds into the Wine codebase, instead preferring to focus solely on improving Wine's implementation of the Windows API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] While this approach focuses Wine development on long-term compatibility, it makes it difficult for users to run applications that require workarounds.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Consequently, many third-party applications have been created to ease the use of those applications that do not work *out of the box* within Wine itself.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The Wine wiki maintains a page of current and obsolete third-party applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The developers of the Direct3D portions of Wine have continued to implement new features such as pixel shaders to increase game support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine can also use native DLLs directly, thus increasing functionality, but then a license for Windows is needed unless the DLLs were distributed with the application itself.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine also includes its own open-source implementations of several Windows programs, such as *Notepad*, *WordPad*, *Control Panel*, *Internet Explorer*, and *Windows Explorer*.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The Wine Application Database (AppDB) is a community-maintained on-line database about which Windows programs works with Wine and how well they work.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine ensures good backward compatibility with legacy Windows applications, including those written for Windows 3.1x.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine can mimic different Windows versions required for some programs, going as far back as Windows 2.0.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] However, Windows 1.x and Windows 2.x support was removed from Wine development version 1.3.12.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] If DOSBox is installed on the system (see below on MS-DOS), Wine development version 1.3.12 and later nevertheless show the "Windows 2.0" option for the Windows version to mimic, but Wine still will not run most Windows 2.0 programs because MS-DOS and Windows functions are not currently integrated.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Backward compatibility in Wine is generally superior to that of Windows, as newer versions of Windows can force users to upgrade legacy Windows applications, and may break unsupported software forever as there is nobody adjusting the program for the changes in the operating system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] In many cases, Wine can offer better legacy support than newer versions of Windows with "Compatibility Mode".
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine can run 16-bit Windows programs (Win16) on a 64-bit operating system, which uses an x86-64 (64-bit) CPU, a functionality not found in 64-bit versions of Microsoft Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] WineVDM allows 16-bit Windows applications to run on 64-bit versions of Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine partially supports Windows console applications, and the user can choose which backend to use to manage the console (choices include raw streams, curses, and user32).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] When using the raw streams or curses backends, Windows applications will run in a Unix terminal.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Preliminary support for 64-bit Windows applications was added to Wine 1.1.10, in December 2008.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of April 2019, the support is considered stable.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The two versions of Wine are built separately, and as a result only building wine64 produces an environment only capable of running x86-64 applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of April 2019, Wine has stable support for a WoW64 build, which allows both 32-bit and 64-bit Windows applications to run inside the same Wine instance.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] To perform such a build, one must first build the 64-bit version, and then build the 32-bit version referencing the 64-bit version.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Just like Microsoft's WoW64, the 32-bit build process will add parts necessary for handling 32-bit programs to the 64-bit build.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] This functionality is seen from at least 2010.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Early versions of Microsoft Windows run on top of MS-DOS, and Windows programs may depend on MS-DOS programs to be usable.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine does not have good support for MS-DOS, but starting with development version 1.3.12, Wine tries running MS-DOS programs in DOSBox if DOSBox is available on the system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Due to a bug, Wine also incorrectly identifies Windows 1.x and Windows 2.x programs as MS-DOS programs, unsuccessfully attempting to run them in DOSBox.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine provides Winelib, which allows its shared-object implementations of the Windows API to be used as actual libraries for a Unix program.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] This allows for Windows code to be built into native Unix executables.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Since October 2010, Winelib also works on the ARM platform.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Support for Solaris SPARC was dropped in version 1.5.26.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine provides some support for ARM (as well as ARM64/AArch64) processors and the Windows flavors that run on it.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of April 2019, Wine can run ARM/Win32 applications intended for unlocked Windows RT devices (but not Windows RT programs).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Windows CE support (either x86 or ARM) is missing, but an unofficial, pre-alpha proof-of-concept version called WineCE allows for some support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] On 3 February 2013 at the FOSDEM talk in Brussels, Alexandre Julliard demonstrated an early demo of Wine running on Google's Android operating system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Experimental builds of WINE for Android (x86 and ARM) were released in late 2017.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It has been routinely updated by the official developers ever since.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The default builds do not implement cross-architecture emulation via QEMU, and as a result ARM versions will only run ARM applications that use the Win32 API.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine, by default, uses specialized Windows builds of Gecko and Mono to substitute for Microsoft's Internet Explorer and .NET Framework.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine has built-in implementations of JScript and VBScript.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It is possible to download and run Microsoft's installers for those programs through winetricks or manually.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Wine is not known to have good support for most versions of Internet Explorer (IE).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Of all the reasonably recent versions, Internet Explorer 8 for Windows XP is the only version that reports a usable rating on Wine's AppDB, out-of-the-box.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] However Google Chrome gets a gold rating (as of Wine 5.5-staging), and Microsoft's IE replacement web browser Edge, is known to be based on that browser (after switching from Microsoft's own rendering engine).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Winetricks offer auto-installation for Internet Explorer 6 through 8, so these versions can be reasonably expected to work with its built-in workarounds.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] An alternative for installing Internet Explorer directly is to use the now-defunct IEs4Linux.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] It is not compatible with the latest versions of Wine, and the development of IEs4Linux is inactive.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The core Wine development aims at a correct implementation of the Windows API as a whole and has sometimes lagged in some areas of compatibility with certain applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Direct3D, for example, remained unimplemented until 1998, although newer releases have had an increasingly complete implementation.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] CodeWeavers markets CrossOver specifically for running Microsoft Office and other major Windows applications, including some games.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] CodeWeavers employs Alexandre Julliard to work on Wine and contributes most of its code to the Wine project under the LGPL.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] CodeWeavers also released a new version called CrossOver Mac for Intel-based Apple Macintosh computers on 10 January 2007.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Unlike upstream wine, CrossOver is notably able to run on the x64-only versions of macOS, using a technique known as "wine32on64".
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As of 2012, CrossOver includes the functionality of both the CrossOver Games and CrossOver Pro lines therefore CrossOver Games and CrossOver Pro are no longer available as single products.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] CrossOver Games was optimized for running Windows video games.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Unlike CrossOver, it didn't focus on providing the most stable version of Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Instead, experimental features are provided to support newer games.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] On 21 August 2018, Valve announced a new variation of Wine, named Proton, designed to integrate with the Linux version of the company's Steam software (including Steam installations built into their Linux-based SteamOS operating system and Steam Machine computers).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Proton entered public beta immediately upon being announced.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Valve had already been collaborating with CodeWeavers since 2016 to develop improvements to Wine's gaming performance, some of which have been merged to the upstream Wine project.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Some of the specific improvements incorporated into Proton include Vulkan-based Direct3D 9, 10, 11, and 12 implementations via vkd3d, DXVK, and D9VK multi-threaded performance improvements via esync, improved handling of fullscreen games, and better automatic game controller hardware support.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Proton is fully open-source and available via GitHub.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Forks of Proton such as 'GEproton' have also become popular.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The Russian company Etersoft has been developing a proprietary version of Wine since 2006.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] WINE@Etersoft supports popular Russian applications (for example, 1C:Enterprise by 1C Company).
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The Wine project has received a number of technical and philosophical complaints and concerns over the years.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Because of Wine's ability to run Windows binary code, concerns have been raised over native Windows viruses and malware affecting Unix-like operating systems as Wine can run limited malware made for Windows.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] A 2018 security analysis found that 5 out of 30 malware samples were able to successfully run through Wine, a relatively low rate that nevertheless posed a security risk.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] For this reason the developers of Wine recommend never running it as the superuser.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Malware research software such as ZeroWine runs Wine on Linux in a virtual machine, to keep the malware completely isolated from the host system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] An alternative to improve the security without the performance cost of using a virtual machine, is to run Wine in an LXC container, as Anbox software is doing by default with Android.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Another security concern is when the implemented specifications are ill-designed and allow for security compromise.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Because Wine implements these specifications, it will likely also implement any security vulnerabilities they contain.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] One instance of this problem was the 2006 Windows Metafile vulnerability, which saw Wine implementing the vulnerable SETABORTPROC escape.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] A common concern about Wine is that its existence means that vendors are less likely to write native Linux, macOS, and BSD applications.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] As an example of this, it is worth considering IBM's 1994 operating system, OS/2 Warp.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] However, OS/2 had many problems with end user acceptance.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Perhaps the most serious was that most computers sold already came with DOS and Windows, and many people didn't bother to evaluate OS/2 on its merits due to already having an operating system.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] "Bundling" of DOS and Windows and the chilling effect this had on the operating system market frequently came up in *United States v.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] The use of Wine for gaming has proved specifically controversial in the Linux community, as some feel it is preventing, or at least hindering, the further growth of native Linux gaming on the platform.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] One quirk however is that Wine is now able to run 16-bit and even certain 32-bit applications and games that do not launch on current 64-bit Windows versions.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] This use-case has led to running Wine on Windows itself via Windows Subsystem for Linux or third-party virtual machines, as well as encapsulated by means such as BoxedWine and otvdm.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] Until 2020, Microsoft had not made any public statements about Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] However, the Windows Update online service blocks updates to Microsoft applications running in Wine.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] On 16 February 2005, Ivan Leo Puoti discovered that Microsoft had started checking the Windows Registry for the Wine configuration key and would block the Windows Update for any component.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] In January 2020, Microsoft cited Wine as a positive consequence of being able to reimplement APIs, in its amicus curiae brief for *Google LLC v.
[src:wine-compatibility-layer/wine-software] In August 2024, Microsoft donated the Mono Project, a reimplementation of the .NET Framework, to the developers of Wine.
